9. Importing bioferineries¶

The biorefineries package includes a design for 2nd generation ethanol production from corntover and a design for the co-production of ethanol and biodiesel from lipidcane [1, 2]. To load the cornstover biorefinery, simply load the system:

[1]:

import biosteam as bst
from biorefineries.cornstover import system

Now your flowsheet should change to the cornstover biorefinery:

[2]:

bst.main_flowsheet

[2]:

<MainFlowsheet: cornstover>

All systems, unit operations, and streams are registered in your flowsheet:

[3]:

bst.main_flowsheet.system

[3]:

Register:
 <System: pretreatment_sys>
 <System: fermentation_sys>
 <System: ethanol_recycle_sys>
 <System: purification>
 <System: aerobic_digestion_sys>
 <System: cornstover_sys>
 <System: Area700>

By convention, the complete biorefinery system begins with the same name as the flowsheet:

[4]:

cornstover_sys = bst.main_flowsheet.system.cornstover_sys
cornstover_sys.diagram()

Similarly, you can also load the lipidcane biorefinery:

[5]:

from biorefineries.lipidcane import system
lipidcane_sys = bst.main_flowsheet.system.lipidcane_sys
lipidcane_sys.diagram()

Note that your main flowsheet is now “lipidcane”:

[6]:

bst.main_flowsheet

[6]:

<MainFlowsheet: lipidcane>

You can switch flowsheets anytime with the set_flowsheet method:

[7]:

bst.main_flowsheet.flowsheet

[7]:

Register:
 <Flowsheet: default>
 <Flowsheet: cornstover>
 <Flowsheet: lipidcane>

[8]:

bst.main_flowsheet.set_flowsheet('default')

[9]:

bst.main_flowsheet

[9]:

<MainFlowsheet: default>

You can also import only the Chemicals object used to model the thermodynamic properties, without having to load the whole biorefinery system:

[10]:

from biorefineries.lipidcane.chemicals import lipidcane_chemicals
lipidcane_chemicals

[10]:

CompiledChemicals([Water, Methanol, Ethanol, Glycerol, Glucose, Sucrose, H3PO4, P4O10, CO2, Octane, O2, Biodiesel, Ash, Cellulose, Hemicellulose, Flocculant, Lignin, Solids, DryYeast, CaO, HCl, NaOH, NaOCH3, Lipid])

References

  1. Huang, H., Long, S., & Singh, V. (2016) “Techno-economic analysis of biodiesel and ethanol co-production from lipid-producing sugarcane” Biofuels, Bioproducts and Biorefining, 10(3), 299–315. https://doi.org/10.1002/bbb.1640

  2. Humbird, D., Davis, R., Tao, L., Kinchin, C., Hsu, D., Aden, A., Dudgeon, D. (2011). Process Design and Economics for Biochemical Conversion of Lignocellulosic Biomass to Ethanol: Dilute-Acid Pretreatment and Enzymatic Hydrolysis of Corn Stover (No. NREL/TP-5100-47764, 1013269). https://doi.org/10.2172/1013269
